>Dream starts in some sort of hospital
>I'm a doctor there, but I end up in a hospital wing I don't recognize
>I look around and see a husky girl in a hospital gown
>One of her eyes is missing and her head and shoulders are covered in bandages
>I get close to her, and she says something to me before someone else takes me away
>Wake up, then go back to sleep
>I'm in a secret military base, a scientist in it
>Something's happened and people are evacuating
>I'm running in the opposite direction, looking for someone
>I find her in a locked cell, the same husky girl from before, but she looks different
>She still has the missing eye, covered up by some bandages, but now she has two heads, the left one looking like it was made of ash, glowing hot coals where its eyes should be, and the right head seems to be made from mud, with pale gray rocks for eyes
>She's naked and cowering in a corner when I find her
>I open her cell and take her out, using my lab coat to cover her up as much as possible
>When we finally leave the facility, we find ourselves in the middle of the desert, something in the sky obscuring the moon
>We hide from the thing while the military fires at it
>During the commotion, we sneak away into a car, me driving her away
>Her ashen head thanks me as she falls asleep in the back of the car.
Something else happened afterwards, but I can't remember it now

Hey, good to hear it'll be sticking around. If it means anything, it didn't seem like there was that much in the way of dead ended exposition / rambling, and the wolves didn't feel like they were shoehorned in at all.

Let me know if I'm reading too far into it, but the closest things to examples I can think of for either are:

Ramblings: If you're talking about your MC just sort of going through his day, a bit of that isn't bad. It can be a decent breakup from the action scene to action scene (E.G. Tuesday morning. Breakfast, tended to garden, ZOMG demon attack! Fire! Brimstone! Jeff got flayed into a meat rainbow!)

If you're looking to justify the MC working with the wolves, you can always play them off as complimentary roles in defense against dark magic. The wolves might maybe be better at sensing demonic entities and be much better/faster/more resilient in combat, while the main could be more of a healer / spellcaster / sorcery-detective. The wolves could root out and kill demons while the main could investigate and pinpoint the cause (would play nicely into the Twig/All story arc.) That the MC is part of a/the church just makes sense in a medieval fantasy world.

I realize it might sound a fuzz hypocritical for me to say not to sweat the justification of every detail. I was, after all, moping about how to turn an Amarok into a were-adlet without being off-putting in the last thread. My counter would be that the further you break from reality land, the less explanation you need. E.G. not many people are going to ask for a justification of FTL in a space opera, but you better be ready to justify a character having a phaser in a 20's detective procedural.


BTW, let me know if my ramblings are helpful, or if I'm digging too deep into your shit. I love talking story / world building, but realize it can be kind of a personal thing.
